================================================================================

- Each byte of character is stored as its ASCII value in hexadecimal.
- Each decimal value is automatically converted to its 16-bit binary equivalent
and stored as a hexadecimal number.
- Processor uses the little-endian byte ordering.
- Negative numbers are converted to its 2's complement representation.
- Short and long floating-point numbers are represented using 32 or 64 bits, 
respectively.
================================================================================

# Examples to define directives:
choice		    DB	'y'
number		    DW	12345
neg_number	    DW	-12345
big_number	    DQ	123456789
real_number1	DD	1.234
real_number2	DQ	123.456

# Examples to reserve directives:
buffer   RESB 100
number01 RESW 2
number02 RESD 1
================================================================================
To define CONSTANTs in .data section, you can use EQU directive
# Examples:
_TOTAL equ 100
_BUF_SIZE equ 64

To redefine CONSTANT in any section, you can use %assign directive
# Examples:
%assign _TOTAL 100
%assign _BUF_SIZE 64

To define MACROS in any section, you can use %define directive
# Examples:
%define PTR [EBP+4]
%define PRINT_CHAR MOV EAX, 4

Can use %undef to undefine the directive.
# Examples:
%undef PRINT_CHAR
================================================================================
The INC instruction is used for incrementing an operand by one.
# Examples:
INC [count]
INC word [EBX]
	
The DEC instruction is used for decrementing an operand by one.
# Examples:
DEC [value]
DEC byte [ESI]

================================================================================
The ADD and SUB instructions are used for performing simple addition/subtraction 
of binary data in byte, word and doubleword size, i.e., for adding or 
subtracting 8-bit, 16-bit or 32-bit operands, respectively.

The ADD/SUB instruction can take place between:
- Register to register
- Memory to register
- Register to memory
- Register to constant data
- Memory to constant data

================================================================================
There are two instructions for multiplying binary data. The MUL (Multiply) 
instruction handles unsigned data and the IMUL (Integer Multiply) handles signed 
data. Both instructions affect the Carry and Overflow flag.

# When two bytes are multiplied: The multiplicand is in the AL register, and the 
multiplier is a byte in the memory or in another register. The product is in AX. 
High-order 8 bits of the product is stored in AH and the low-order 8 bits are 
stored in AL.

AL x 8bit source = AH AL
---

# When two one-word values are multiplied: The multiplicand should be in the AX 
register, and the multiplier is a word in memory or another register. For example, 
for an instruction like MUL DX, you must store the multiplier in DX and the 
multiplicand in AX.

The resultant product is a doubleword, which will need two registers. The 
high-order (leftmost) portion gets stored in DX and the lower-order (rightmost) 
portion gets stored in AX.

AX x 16bit source = DX AX
---

# When two doubleword values are multiplied
When two doubleword values are multiplied, the multiplicand should be in EAX and 
the multiplier is a doubleword value stored in memory or in another register. 
The product generated is stored in the EDX:EAX registers, i.e., the high order 
32 bits gets stored in the EDX register and the low order 32-bits are stored in 
the EAX register.

EAX x 32bit source = EDX EAX
---

# Examples:
MOV AL, 10
MOV DL, 25
MUL DL
...
MOV DL, 0FFH	; DL= -1
MOV AL, 0BEH	; AL = -66
IMUL DL
---

MOV	AL,'3'  ; get char 3 in ASCII
SUB AL, '0' ; convert ASCII to decimal

MOV BL, '2' ; get char 3 in ASCII
SUB BL, '0' ; convert ASCII to decimal
MUL BL      ; multiply BL to AL and storage result in AL
ADD	AL, '0' ; convert result in AL to ASCII

================================================================================
The division operation generates two elements - a quotient and a remainder. In 
case of multiplication, overflow does not occur because double-length registers 
are used to keep the product. However, in case of division, overflow may occur. 
The processor generates an interrupt if overflow occurs.

The DIV (Divide) instruction is used for unsigned data and the IDIV (Integer 
Divide) is used for signed data.

# When the divisor is 1 byte
The dividend is assumed to be in the AX register (16 bits). After division, the 
quotient goes to the AL register and the remainder goes to the AH register.

AX(16bit) / (8bit)  = AL(Quotient) AH(Remainder)
---

# When the divisor is 1 byte
The dividend is assumed to be in the AX register (16 bits). After division, the 
quotient goes to the AL register and the remainder goes to the AH register.

(DX AX)(32bit) / (16bit) = AX(Quotient) DX(Remainder)
---

# When the divisor is doubleword
The dividend is assumed to be 64 bits long and in the EDX:EAX registers. The 
high-order 32 bits are in EDX and the low-order 32 bits are in EAX. After 
division, the 32-bit quotient goes to the EAX register and the 32-bit remainder 
goes to the EDX register.

(EDX EAX)(64bit) / (32bit) = EAX(Quotient) EDX(Remainder)
---

# Examples:
; The following example divides 8 with 2. 
; The dividend 8 is stored in the 16-bit AX register and 
; the divisor 2 is stored in the 8-bit BL register.

MOV	AX, '8' ; get char 8 in ASCII
SUB AX, '0' ; convert ASCII to decimal

MOV BL, '2' ; get char 2 in ASCII
SUB BL, '0' ; convert ASCII to decimal
DIV BL
ADD	AX, '0'
================================================================================